ngle Parents (TV series)|Single Parents]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n| Episode: \"Yarn and Pebbles\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1321658}}\n*[http://www.firejoemorgan.com Fire Joe Morgan]\n*[http://royalsblog.kansascity.com/?q=node/35 Interview] with Michael Schur\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080907123104/http://www.whps.org/whps/spotlight/where-in-the-world/tv-writer-mike-schur Where are they now?] Interview About His Public Schooling\n\n{{EmmyAward ComedyVarietyMusicWriting 2000s}}\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicComedyScreenplay 2000s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schur, Michael}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard Lampoon alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Showrunners]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ann Arbor, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American television producer and writer}}\n{{About||the electronics researcher|Michael Shur|the political reporter|Michael Shure}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael Schur\n| image         = Michael Schur 2012 (cropped).jpg\n| caption       = Schur at the 2012 [[Peabody Award]]s\n| birth_name    = Michael Herbert Schur\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1975|10|29}}\n| birth_place   = [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]], U.S.\n| residence     = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = Ken Tremendous\n| alma_mater    = [[Harvard University]]\n| occupation    = [[Television producer]], [[screenwriter]]\n| years_active  = 1997\u2013present\n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[J. J. Philbin]]|October 2005}}\n| children      = 2\n| relatives     = \n}}\n\n'''Michael Herbert Schur'''<ref name=\"Wedding\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/09/fashion/weddings/09phil.html|title=Jennifer Philbin and Michael Schur|date=2005-10-09|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2008-09-15|quote=Mr. Schur, 29...}}</ref> (born October 29, 1975)<ref name=\"Wedding\" /> is an American television producer, writer, and actor. He was a producer and writer for the comedy series ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'', and co-created ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' with ''Office'' producer [[Greg Daniels]]. He created ''[[The Good Place]]'', co-created the comedy series ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'' and was a producer on the series ''[[Master of None]]''.\n\nSchur's comedies typically include large, diverse casts and have created break-out stars. His shows feature optimistic characters who often find lasting love and strong friendships,<ref name=\"tvinsider\">{{cite news |last1=Hannemann |first1=Emily |title=The Magic of Michael Schur's Sitcoms: Why 'The Good Place,' 'Parks and Rec' & More Are So Rewatchable |url=https://www.tvinsider.com/715001/michael-schur-shows-similarities-good-place-the-office/ |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |work=TV Insider |date=September 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Leishman |first1=Rachel |title=Mike Schur's Shows Have The Most Relatable Characters on Television |url=https://www.themarysue.com/mike-schur-shows-teh-feels/ |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |publisher=TheMarySue.com |date=September 17, 2018 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The Chemistry of Cluelessness in Michael Schur's Sitcoms |url=https://www.popmatters.com/michael-schurs-comedies-2580354381.html |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |publisher=PopMatters.com |date=July 12, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> through plots that showcase \"good-hearted humanistic warmth.\"<ref name=\"nytimes2018\">{{cite news |last1=Anderson |first1=Sam |title=What Makes 'The Good Place' So Good? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2018/10/04/magazine/good-place-michael-schur-philosophy.html |accessdate=February 10, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=October 4, 2018}}</ref> Schur has been nominated for 14 [[Primetime Emmy Award]]s, winning two for his work on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' (1997\u20132004) and ''The Office''.<ref name=\"emmys\">{{cite web |title=Michael Schur |url=https://www.emmys.com/bios/michael-schur |publisher=Television Academy |accessdate=February 10, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSchur was born in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]], [[Michigan]], to a family of [[Jewish]] background.<ref>https://forward.com/culture/437657/what-the-good-place-says-about-jewish-ethics/</ref> His parents are Warren M. Schur and Anne Herbert, and he was raised in [[West Hartford, Connecticut|West Hartford]], [[Connecticut]].<ref name=\"Wedding\" /><ref>{{cite tweet|user=KenTremendous|author=Ken Tremendous|number=303332060137926656|date=18 February 2013|title=@williamfleitch I need no such reminding. I was born in Ann Arbor.}}</ref> He first became interested in comedy when he was 11 years old, when he read ''[[Without Feathers]]'', a 1975 collection of humorous essays by [[Woody Allen]]. Schur said he found the book on his father's bookshelf and stayed up reading it until 4 a.m.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Martin |first=Denise |title=Making bureaucracy work: How NBC's \"Parks and Recreation\" overcame bad buzz |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2009-11-18 |location=[[Los Angeles]], [[California]] |url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2009/11/parks-and-recreation.html |accessdate=2009-12-06}}</ref>\n\nSchur attended [[William H. Hall High School]] in [[West Hartford, Connecticut]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Gendreau|first=LeAnne|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/the-scene/archive/West-Hartford-Guy-Makes-Parks-and-Rec-Funny-.html|title=West Hartford Guy Behind Poehler's \"Parks & Recreation\"|date=7 April 2009|publisher=[[WVIT]]|accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref> Schur graduated [[Phi Beta Kappa]] with a B.A. from  [[Harvard University]] in 1997, where he was a president of the ''[[Harvard Lampoon]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2005/4/15/how-harvard-remade-the-office-whither/|title=How Harvard Remade 'The Office'|work= [[The Harvard Crimson]]|access-date=2016-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nStarting in 1998, Schur was a writer on NBC's ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/showrunners-2012-parks-recreations-mike-schur-375657|title=Showrunners 2012: 'Parks and Recreation's' Mike Schur|last=Goldberg|first=Lesley|date=October 3, 2012|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=August 12, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/culture/2017/1/9/14202016/netflix-comedy-good-place|title=The Good Place\u2019s creator explains why not every comedy is better off as a Netflix original|last=VanDerWerff|first=Emily|date=January 9, 2018|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=October 6, 2019}}</ref> Schur became the producer of ''[[Weekend Update]]'' in 2001; his first show in the new role was ''Saturday Night Live's'' first episode after the [[September 11 attacks]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vulture.com/2015/09/mike-schur-on-writing-comedy-after-911.html|title=Mike Schur on How 9/11 Influenced the Writing on SNL, The Office, and Parks and Rec|last=Schur|first=Mike|date=September 11, 2016|website=Vulture.com|publisher=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=August 12, 2018|language=en}}</ref> In [[54th Primetime Emmy Awards|2002]], he won his first [[Primetime Emmy Award]] as part of ''SNL''{{'}}s writing team.<ref name=\"emmys\"/> Schur left ''Saturday Night Live'' in 2004.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/zap-michaelschurnbcdeal-story.html|title=More Money for Mose at 'The Office'|last=Zap2it|first=|date=August 19, 2008|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=August 12, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref>\n\nSoon afterward, he became producer and writer for ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' on NBC, for which he wrote ten episodes and won the [[58th Primetime Emmy Awards|2006]] [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series|Emmy Award for Outstanding Comedy Series]]. Schur appeared on ''The Office'' as [[Dwight Schrute|Dwight]]'s cousin [[List of characters from The Office (US T.V. series)#Mose Schrute|Mose]] in several episodes, including \"[[Initiation (The Office)|Initiation]]\", in which Dwight takes [[Ryan Howard (The Office)|Ryan]] to his [[beet]] farm, \"[[Money (The Office)|Money]]\", in which Jim and Pam spend a night at the farm, \"[[The Deposition (The Office)|The Deposition]]\", \"[[Koi Pond (The Office)|Koi Pond]]\", \"[[Counseling (The Office)|Counseling]]\" and \"[[Finale (The Office)|Finale]]\". He also co-wrote ''[[List of The Office (U.S. TV series) episodes#Webisodes|The Office: The Accountants]]'' [[webisode]]s with [[Paul Lieberstein]].\n\nIn 2005, Schur served as a co-producer of [[HBO]]'s ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]'' and wrote two of its 13 episodes.\n\nSchur also wrote for [[Fire Joe Morgan]], a [[sports journalism]] blog, under the pseudonym \"Ken Tremendous\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firejoemorgan.com/2005/04/about-us.html|title=Fire Joe Morgan: About Us|publisher=firejoemorgan.com|accessdate=31 October 2012}}</ref> Schur resurrected the pen name on March 31, 2011, when he began writing for [[SB Nation]]'s Baseball Nation site.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Buchanan|first1=Ben|title=Introducing Baseball Nation|url=http://www.overthemonster.com/2011/3/31/2083705/introducing-baseball-nation|accessdate=21 December 2016|work=OverTheMonster.com|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|date=31 March 2011}}</ref> Ken Tremendous is also Schur's [[Twitter]] username.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ken Tremendous (@KenTremendous)|url=https://twitter.com/kentremendous|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=21 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Schur and [[Greg Daniels]] started working on a pilot for ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' as a proposed [[spin-off (media)|spin-off]] of ''The Office''.<ref name=\":0\" /> Over time, Schur realized ''Parks and Recreation'' would work better if they made it separate from ''The Office''. While ''Parks and Recreation'' received negative reviews in its first season, it received critical acclaim in the second, much like ''The Office''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cormier |first1=Roger |title=18 Facts About ''Parks and Recreation'' |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/61045/18-things-you-may-not-know-about-parks-and-recreation |accessdate=November 30, 2018 |work=[[Mental Floss]] |date=January 11, 2016 |language=en |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6yaBydu0N?url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/61045/18-things-you-may-%20%20not-know-about-parks-and-recreation |archive-date=April 10, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nSchur collaborated with [[The Decemberists]] on their music video for \"Calamity Song\" from the album ''[[The King Is Dead (album)|The King Is Dead]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Carlin|first=Shannon|title=First Watch: The Decemberists, 'Calamity Song'|publisher=[[NPR]]|date=2011-08-22|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/allsongs/2011/08/22/139033489/first-watch-the-decemberists-calamity-song |accessdate=2011-08-23}}</ref> This video is based upon Eschaton, a mock-nuclear war game played on tennis courts that [[David Foster Wallace]] created in his 1996 novel ''[[Infinite Jest]]''. Schur wrote his undergraduate senior thesis on the novel,<ref>{{Cite web|last=Hyden|first=Steve|title=Parks And Recreation's Michael Schur talks about directing the Decemberists\u2019 new Infinite Jest-themed video|publisher=The Onion A.V. Club|date=2011-08-22|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/parks-and-recreations-michael-schur-talks-about-di,60764/ |accessdate=2012-11-18}}</ref> and he also owns the film rights to it.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Busis|first=Hillary|title=Last night's Parks and Rec was an extended homage to Infinite Jest|publisher=EW|url=http://popwatch.ew.com/2013/04/05/parks-and-recreation-infinite-jest/|accessdate=2013-05-12}}</ref>\n\nWith [[Dan Goor|Daniel J. Goor]], Schur created the cop comedy ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'', which premiered in fall 2013 on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]]. The show was moved to NBC in its sixth season. The show boasts six awards.\n\nOn September 19, 2016, the Schur-created sitcom ''[[The Good Place]]'' began airing on [[NBC]].<ref name= \"goodplace\">{{cite news |last=Dodson |first=P. Claire |url= http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/tv/q-and-a/a48706/the-good-place-michael-schur-interview/ |title=''The Good Place'' Creator Michael Schur Has an Idea of Who's Going to Make It to Heaven |work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |date=2016-09-19 |accessdate=2016-09-23}}</ref> The supernatural series concerning philosophy and being a good person, starring [[Kristen Bell]] and [[Ted Danson]], became a surprise critical and commercial success<ref name=\"nytimes2018\"/>, concluding its four-season run on January 30, 2020.\n\nIn 2016, Schur and [[Rashida Jones]] co-wrote the teleplay of \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\", an episode of the television [[anthology series]] ''[[Black Mirror]]'',  from a story by [[Charlie Brooker]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2016/07/27/black-mirror-season-3-rashida-jones-mike-schur-episode/|title=Black Mirror Enlists Rashida Jones and Mike Schur for Season 3 Writing Stint|work=TVLine|first=Vlada|last=Gelman|date=27 July 2016|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Schur joined other WGA writers in firing their agents as part of the [[Writers Guild of America|WGA's]] stand against the [[Association of Talent Agents|ATA]] and the unfair practice of [[Movie packaging|packaging]].<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Patton Oswalt, David Simon, Danny Zuker, More WGA Members Post Termination Letters |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/wga-members-termination-letters-1203189062/ |magazine=Variety}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSchur is married to [[J. J. Philbin]], who was formerly a writer on ''[[The O.C.]]'' and is the daughter of television star [[Regis Philbin]]. Their son was born in February 2008 and daughter born in July 2010.<ref name=\"people-2008\">{{cite news|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20178757,00.html|title=Regis Philbin Is a Grandfather!|date=2008-02-19|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|accessdate=2012-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Essany |first1=Michael |title=Regis Philbin |date=2011 |publisher=Hyperink Inc |isbn=9781614648062 |page=32 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VcN-BwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT32&pg=PT32 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! width=\"33\" | Year !!  Title !! width=65 | [[Film director|Director]] !! width=65 | [[Screenwriter|Writer]] !! width=65 | [[Film producer|Producer]] !! width=65 | [[Actor]] !! width=65 | [[Executive producer]] !! | Creator !! width=65 | Role !! Notes\n|- \n|1997\u20132004\n| ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes|[[Weekend Update]]}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| Various roles\n| Wrote 138 episodes, appeared in 3 episodes\n|-\n|2005\n| ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n| Wrote 2 episodes\n|-\n|2005\u20132013\n| ''[[The Office (U.S. TV series)|The Office]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| Mose Schrute\n| Wrote 12 episodes, appeared in 13 episodes\n|-\n|2006\n| ''[[Totally Awesome]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n| [[Television film]]\n|-\n|2007\n| ''[[The O.C.]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| Paul\n| Episode: \"The Case of the Franks\"\n|-\n|2008\n| ''[[Miss Guided]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| Male Teacher\n| Episode: \"Pool Party\"\n|-\n|2009\u20132015\n| ''[[Parks and Recreation]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| Wrote 19 episodes, directed 9 episodes<br />Non-speaking cameo in Season 6 episode: \"Second Chunce\"\n|-\n|2013\u2013present\n| ''[[Brooklyn Nine-Nine]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| Wrote 2 episodes, directed 2 episodes\n|-\n|2015\u20132017\n| ''[[Master of None]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n| \n|-\n|2016\u20132020\n| ''[[The Good Place]]'' \n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| \n| Wrote 5 episodes, directed 4 episodes\n|-\n|2016\n| ''[[Black Mirror]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n| Episode: \"[[Nosedive (Black Mirror)|Nosedive]]\"<br/>Co-wrote teleplay with [[Rashida Jones]]\n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Abby's]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n| \n|-\n|2019\n| ''[[Sunnyside (American TV series)|Sunnyside]]'' \n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| \n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Single Parents (TV series)|Single Parents]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n| {{no}}\n|\n| Episode: \"Yarn and Pebbles\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1321658}}\n*[http://www.firejoemorgan.com Fire Joe Morgan]\n*[http://royalsblog.kansascity.com/?q=node/35 Interview] with Michael Schur\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080907123104/http://www.whps.org/whps/spotlight/where-in-the-world/tv-writer-mike-schur Where are they now?] Interview About His Public Schooling\n\n{{EmmyAward ComedyVarietyMusicWriting 2000s}}\n{{WritersGuildofAmericaEpisodicComedyScreenplay 2000s}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schur, Michael}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American television producers]]\n[[Category:American television writers]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard Lampoon alumni]]\n[[Category:People from West Hartford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Writers Guild of America Award winners]]\n[[Category:Showrunners]]\n[[Category:Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Ann Arbor, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Michigan]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n", "name_user": "2001:8003:488a:9a00:198f:1035:ac7:d7b9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Michael Chu is Michael Simmie)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Schur"}
{"title_page": "South Island School", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = South Island School\n| image = South Island School Badge.png\n| imagesize = 74\n| caption = South Island School's logo\n| established = 1977\n| type = [[Private school|Private]], [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]], [[International School|international]], [[Primary school|primary]], [[coeducational|co-educational]].\n| motto = Making a Difference\n| principal = Mr. Tom Vignoles\n| enrollment = approx. 1,400<ref>[http://www.esf.edu.hk/inydex.aspx?nodeID=985&langNo=1]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| language = English\n| free_label = Year\n| free_text = 7 - 13\n| houses = ''Bahay, Casa, Shtepi, Namas, Kuca, Maison\n| mascot = Stingrays\n| colours = Green, white and blue\n| location = 50 Nam Fung Road<br />[[Aberdeen, Hong Kong]]\n| website = http://www.sis.edu.hk/\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|t=\u5357\u5cf6\u4e2d\u5b78\n|s=\u5357\u5c9b\u4e2d\u5b66\n|j=Naam4 dou2 zung1 hok6\n|y=N\u00e0ahm d\u00f3u j\u016bng hohk\n|p=N\u00e1n D\u01ceo Zh\u014dngxu\u00e9\n}}\n'''South Island School''' ({{zh|t=\u5357\u5cf6\u4e2d\u5b78}}) is a private school founded by the [[English Schools Foundation]] of Hong Kong, and is located at 50 Nam Fung Road, [[Aberdeen, Hong Kong|Aberdeen]], [[Hong Kong]], with about 1,400 students enrolled and 107 teachers. Students come from diverse backgrounds, with over 38 nationalities represented. The school offers the [[GCSE]]/[[IGCSE]] syllabus, [[IB Diploma Programme]], IB Career-related Programme and the [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTEC]] qualification. The school is one of three ESF secondary schools on Hong Kong Island, the others being [[West Island School]] and [[Island School]].\n\nAccording to an inspection report from 2019 by the Council of International Schools (CoIS) and the Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC), South Island School 'passionately promotes the development of global citizenship and intercultural learning, and the school climate is such that there is a very strong sense of mutual trust amongst all the school's stakeholders.'<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School \u2013 A Celebration of Excellence |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/south-island-school-a-celebration-of-excellence/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nIn 1977, South Island School was founded as an annex of [[Island School]], a fellow [[English Schools Foundation]] School. The school opened with 165 students and 6 teachers, with three classes in Form 1, and one class in Form 2 and Form 3 respectively. Mike Taylor was the first principal. \n\nThe school moved to its current location at 50 Nam Fung Road in 1983. It consisted of the [[Ching Ling Soong]] Block and an outdoor swimming pool.<ref>{{cite web |title=The History of South Island School |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/history/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the school grew in size, more facilities were required. The next big change to the school came with the construction of the Stephen Hawking Building (named after physicist [[Stephen Hawking]]), and the swimming pool became an indoor one with the Sports Block being built on top of it, allowing for year-round swimming lessons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sis.edu.hk/Warps/Principal%20Msg/Autumn%2004.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051113033219/http://www.sis.edu.hk/Warps/Principal%20Msg/Autumn%2004.html |archivedate=13 November 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy 2003, the increase in student population warranted the construction of a new school block. Construction began on a new eight-storey building that would accompany the C Block and the S Block. By 2004, the new block was completed and was named the Da Vinci (after Italian polymath, [[Leonardo da Vinci]]) Block.\n\nIn the school year of 2007\u20132008, the school was accredited to teach the IB Diploma programme. The IB Centre was opened, a section of the school designated for [[International Baccalaureate]] students in Years 12 and 13. This was renamed the Diploma Centre in the school year of 2009\u20132010. \n\nIn November 2010, the new John Wray Atrium, named after previous principal, John Wray, opened for all students.\n\nIn the following years, many of the school facilities underwent renovations. The library in the C Block was renovated in the summer holidays of 2012 and re-opened in late September the same year, and was renamed as the \"Learning Resource Center\". In November 2012, the renovation of the library was completed, and was reopened as the Learning Resources Centre (LRC).\n\nIn February 2014, additional floors were added to the Sports Block to create The Space, a multipurpose learning space. There is also an astroturf on top of the Space which was completed in the same year. In November, the school completed a redesigned School Hall with state-of-the-art facilities and a 400-seat auditorium.\n\nIn 2016, South Island School adopted the Middle Years Program and the IB CP (career-related) programme. The IB CP was offered in addition to the IB Diploma programme, which places greater emphasis on developing vocational skills. The programme combines academic courses from the IB Diploma programme with the career-related experiences of the BTEC courses to create a personalised and career-focused pathway for students.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School's new IB curriculum offer |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/south-island-schools-new-ib-curriculum-offer/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=23 September 2016}}</ref> Also in the same year, the School Foyer and the Refectory were renovated.\n\nIn 2017, South Island School celebrated its 40th anniversary. Students and staff walked down to Deep Water Bay Beach for charity and participated in activities commemorating the event, such as a time capsule and an art mural.<ref>{{cite web |title=Student Council: Catering, Interhouse and more on SIS40 |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/south-island-school-student-council/6617-catering-interhouse-and-more-on-sis-40/1371531516268749/ |website=SIS Student Council Facebook page |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> A giant birthday cake was also made, with enough cake for every teacher and student in the school. Later that October, an exhibition was shown in the Atrium commemorating the school's history \n<ref>{{cite web |title=SIS 40th Birthday Celebration - Archive Exhibition Tour |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/sis-40th-birthday-celebration-archive-exhibition-tour/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=27 October 2017}}</ref>, and an alumni gathering was held in Hong Kong.\n\nIn 2018, the Food Technology laboratories were renovated, along with the Science classrooms on the 6th floor. In 2019, the classrooms on the 3rd and 4th floors of the C Block were also renovated.\n\n== Governance ==\n\nSouth Island School is part of the English Schools Foundation of 22 schools<ref name=\"About ESF\">{{cite web |title=About ESF |url=https://www.esf.edu.hk/about-esf/ |website=ESF |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> in Hong Kong that operates within the ESF government ordinance.\n\nThe school is accountable to the Board of Governors (Executive Committee) of [[English Schools Foundation]] and its local governing body: School Council. The council meets around six times per year. It has two sub-committees, namely Finance & Personnel (FP) and Learning and Professional Development (LPD) both chaired by community representatives. Among other matters, the FP sub-committee reviews the school's annual budget and recommends acceptance to the full council. It also reviews personnel matters and considers health & safety issues. The LPD subcommittee's work is more aimed at, inter alia, curriculum development, teaching methods and examination performance.<ref>http://www.sis.edu.hk/about-us/school-council</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\n\n=== Curriculum ===\nBetween Year 7 and Year 9, students take the Middle Years Programme (MYP) offered by the International Baccalaureate. The MYP is usually a 5-year programme, but the programme was shortened to 3 years so that the IGCSE programme could still be offered. During Year 7 and 8, all students follow a common curriculum, which includes English, Maths, Science, Chinese, a modern foreign language (French or Spanish), Individuals and Societies, Global Thinking, design, and the arts. At the end of Year 9, all students participate in the Community Project. Students work in groups to investigate, propose, plan and implement a project that serves a need within the school community or the wider Hong Kong community.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family Bauhinia Newsletter (June 2019) |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/family-bauhinia-newsletter-june-2019/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |location=Curriculum Update |date=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring Year 10 and 11, students follow the I/GCSE curriculum. All students must take English, Mathematics, Sciences (Biology, Chemistry, Physics), PE (examined or non-examined), a language, a humanities subject, and Global Citizenship. In addition, students can choose to take either another language, or another humanities subject.<ref>{{cite web |title=Y10-11 Curriculum |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/academic/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Year 12 and 13, students can either choose to do the IB Diploma or the IB Career-related Programme. For the Diploma Programme, students must choose 3 Higher Level subjects and 3 Standard Level subjects, where subjects in the student's first language, additional Language, the humanities, the sciences, mathematics are required. Students also need to complete the Extended Essay, CAS, and the Theory of Knowledge course. Students in the Career-related Programme can choose to substitute some of their IB DP subjects with more applied BTEC subjects, but must still complete the CP core.\n\n=== Higher Education Destinations ===\n\nIn 2019, 40% of South Island School students matriculate to the [[United Kingdom]], 19% to [[Hong Kong]], 13% to the [[United States]], 9% to [[Canada]], 6% to either [[Australia]] or New Zealand, and the remainder matriculate to countries such as [[Korea]] and [[Japan]]. In Hong Kong, 17 students chose to study at the [[University of Hong Kong]], five to [[HKUST]] and six to the [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]], while in the UK, 6 students matriculated to [[Imperial College]] and [[University College London|UCL]]. In addition, the most popular universities in Canada were the [[University of British Columbia]] and the [[University of Toronto]] with five students each. \n\nSouth Island School graduates usually apply to a range of courses. Fields such as Economics, and Business and Management have been consistently popular among South Island School graduates. Ten students each have matriculated to the traditionally popular Law and Psychology courses. The social sciences remain popular: a particular favourite is Psychology, with 11 students choosing this as their major. 20 students pursued creative degrees such as Design, Film and Performing Arts as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School Higher Education Destinations 2019 |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/careers-and-higher-education/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Examination Results ===\nIn 2012, 3 students scored the maximum 45 points on the IB Diploma (out of 109 worldwide), and another 5 students scored 44 points. 32% of the graduating body scored 40 points or more. The mean score was 36.3 out of 45, in comparison to the world average of 30.1.<ref>{{cite web|title=IB Results - July 2012|url=http://www.sis.edu.hk/learning-sis/exams-information/ib-exam-results|accessdate=22 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114014713/http://www.sis.edu.hk/learning-sis/exams-information/ib-exam-results|archive-date=14 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, 2 students scored the maximum 45 points on the IB Diploma, while three others scored 44, and a further six scored 43, exceeding international averages by substantial margins. In 2018, 98% of students achieved the full IB Diploma, compared to 78.4% worldwide. That year, the mean score for all IB Diploma students was 35.0 in comparison to the world average of 30.0. Furthermore, 22% of students at South Island School achieved 30 or more points, compared to 8% worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School: IB Diploma Provisional Results (May 2018) |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/IB-Results-2018_for-website.pdf |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Students ==\n\nStudents come from diverse backgrounds, with 38 nationalities represented as of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=For New Families |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/for-new-families/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |location=Student's Welcome}}</ref> In 2019, the most represented was those with United Kingdom citizenship. As of that year, 50% of the students were ethnic Chinese, 14% were Caucasian, 8% were Eurasian, 7% were Indian, and 21% were of other races<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Report 2018-2019 |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/annual-report-2018-2019/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |page=27 |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe school is non-selective towards academic ability and reserves 24 places in the Learning Support Unit for students with additional learning needs.\n\n== Student Leadership ==\n\n=== Prefect Team ===\nThe school has a well-established prefect system in which the Year 12 and Year 13 students are assigned key positions of responsibility to help with the day-to-day operations of the school. Serving as chief representatives of the student body is the Head Prefect team, led by the Head Boy and Head Girl. The Head Prefect Team is selected through a rigorous process that includes written applications, student and teacher voting, a panel interview, and a final interview with the Principal, Vice Principal, and a School Council member.\n\n=== Student Council ===\n\n=== Sustainability Council ===\nThe Sustainability Council, or SusCo in short are a student group that promote environmental awareness in South Island School. Aside from installing water fountains and recycling bins around the school, they have installed solar panels on the roof of the D Block.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Environmental Sustainability Group |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/the-environmental-sustainability-group/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> They have also sold reusable cutlery sets in January 2019 in response to the loss of metal cutlery from the school cafeteria. In March, they raised awareness of environmental issues by organising a 'Green Week'. During this week, they organised a talk raising awareness about plastic use, served meatless meals in the cafeteria for one day, and conducted a 'Power Down Day' where no electrical devices were allowed to be used. In August, they successfully introduced reusable bowls, plates and containers to replace the disposable plates and cups for snacks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Green Catering at SIS |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/next-week-is-green-week/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Making a Difference Council ===\nThe MaD Council are a student group that promotes the school's philosophy of 'Making A Difference'. They are responsible for organising and making decisions for MaD Week, a week where students go overseas or stay in Hong Kong to make a difference to themselves and the community around them. In addition, they work with the House Councils to organise school events and initiatives, such as each House's MaD Weeks, as well as the student-led events.\n\n=== Digital Leaders ===\nThe Digital Leaders are a student group involved in organising technology-related initiatives at South Island School. They have worked with Year 8 InterD students and have supported them in the media literacy unit, as well as supported the Laptop Induction evenings for Year 7s. They have also organised a photography club and coding club, as well as organised an 'Internet Safety Week'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Digital Leadership Team |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/digital-leadership-team/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Internet Safety Week 2019 |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/internet-safety-week-2019-monday-11th-february-monday-18th-february/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Houses ==\nStudents at South Island School were originally allocated into one of seven houses, named after notable people in history. These houses were:\n\n* Hillary (blue)\n* Tolstoy (red)\n* Aylward (yellow)\n* Schweitzer (green)\n* Jefferson (purple)\n* Marden (orange)\n* Nobel (light blue)\n\nThese 7 houses later were then reorganised to form six houses and were named after the word 'House' in six different languages. \n\nThese houses, along with their respective colours and the language where their name originates from, are:\n\n* Bahay (Yellow) - [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n* Casa (Red) - [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n* Shtepi (Green) - [[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n* Maison (Blue) - [[French language|French]]\n* Ku\u0107a (Purple) - [[Croatian language|Croatian]]\n* Namas (Orange) - [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]\n\nThe house colours were allocated after each head of house pulled slips of paper from a hat with a colour written on them. In each year, a house consists of two tutor groups of about 18 students, headed by a tutor of one tutor group, who oversee the students' well-being and performance in school. There is a small 10-minute period at the beginning of each weekday (except for Tuesdays, where the tutor period lasts for half an hour, and Fridays, where there is also another half an hour period before school ends) where all students meet with their tutors. The houses are then grouped into three separate \"Learning Families\", named [[Bamboo]] (consisting of students in Years 9\u201313 in the Kuca, Maison and Namas houses), [[Banyan]] (consisting of students in Years 9\u201313 in the Bahay, Casa and Shtepi houses), and [[Bauhinia]] (all students in Years 7-8). Each house is headed by a Head of House which liaises with student leaders in that particular house.\n\n== Sports and Activities ==\nExtra-curricular activities at the school include [[debating]], [[Model United Nations|MUN]], [[squash (sport)|squash]], [[netball]], [[basketball]], [[Association football|football]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[chess]], [[tennis]], singing, [[Rugby football|rugby]], [[field hockey]], [[cricket]] and more. Every student is obliged to take part in inter-house [[sport of athletics|athletics]], and inter-house swimming. As well as inter-house competitions, South Island School competes in various inter-school competitions such as basketball and football. There are also musical activities culminating in a range of performances throughout the year.<ref>[http://www.sis.edu.hk/index.aspx?nodeid=1162&langNo=1 South Island School - Activities Programme<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926232701/http://www.sis.edu.hk/index.aspx?nodeid=1162&langNo=1 |date=26 September 2007 }}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, South Island School beat Island School to win the All Hong Kong Schools Jing Ying Football Tournament. This was the first time that the school has won.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School won the 2019 Jing Ying Football Tournament |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/south-island-school-won-the-2019-jing-ying-football-tournament/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Joanne Ma |title=South Island School defeats Island School in Jing Ying Football Tournament |url=All Hong Kong Schools Jing Ying Football Tournament |website=Young Post |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe school also organises events such as Nightfest, International Evening, the Innovation Fashion Show, [[Diwali]] Night, the ICM yearly fundraiser, etc. Such events are wholly managed by the student body.\n\n== Campus and Facilities ==\n\nThe school's campus is in the south side of [[Hong Kong Island]] against the backdrop of [[Mount Nicholson]], facing the [[South China Sea]]. It is in a semi-rural location. Students have their own locker and form room. For Years 12 to 13, there is a dedicated study facility and common room space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sis.edu.hk/about-us/campus-and-facilities |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428231946/http://www.sis.edu.hk/about-us/campus-and-facilities |archivedate=28 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFacilities include:\n* The Space (multi-purpose venue)\n* The John Wray Atrium (contains a cafeteria) \n* 25m Indoor Swimming Pool\n* Sports Hall\n* Fitness Gym\n* Artificial Astro Turf\n* 2 Outdoor Playgrounds (Upper and Lower) \n* Covered Playground\n* Covered Multi-Sports Area\n* Hall\n* 2 Drama Studios\n* 12 Science Laboratories\n* 4 Design Technology Workshops\n* 2 Food Technology Workshops\n* 2 Large Art Rooms\n* 3 Media Studies Rooms\n* 2 Music Rooms (Contains 6 smaller music rooms)\n* Refectory\n* Cafe\n* Learning Resource Centre (Library)\n* Diploma Centre\n\n==See also==\n* [[English Schools Foundation]]\n* [[List of English Schools Foundation schools]]\n* [[List of international schools in Hong Kong]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|South Island School}}\n*[http://www.sis.edu.hk/ Official website]\n{{Southern District, Hong Kong}}\n{{International schools in Hong Kong}}\n{{Esfschool}}\n{{coord|22.2539|114.1831|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1977]]\n[[Category:English Schools Foundation schools]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen, Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Hong Kong]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use Hong Kong English|date=December 2016}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name = South Island School\n| image = South Island School Badge.png\n| imagesize = 74\n| caption = South Island School's logo\n| established = 1977\n| type = [[Private school|Private]], [[Comprehensive school|comprehensive]], [[International School|international]], [[Primary school|primary]], [[coeducational|co-educational]].\n| motto = Making a Difference\n| principal = Mr. Tom Vignoles\n| enrollment = approx. 1,400<ref>[http://www.esf.edu.hk/inydex.aspx?nodeID=985&langNo=1]{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| language = English\n| free_label = Year\n| free_text = 7 - 13\n| houses = ''Bahay, Casa, Shtepi, Namas, Kuca, Maison\n| mascot = Stingrays\n| colours = Green, white and blue\n| location = 50 Nam Fung Road<br />[[Aberdeen, Hong Kong]]\n| website = http://www.sis.edu.hk/\n}}\n{{Chinese\n|t=\u5357\u5cf6\u4e2d\u5b78\n|s=\u5357\u5c9b\u4e2d\u5b66\n|j=Naam4 dou2 zung1 hok6\n|y=N\u00e0ahm d\u00f3u j\u016bng hohk\n|p=N\u00e1n D\u01ceo Zh\u014dngxu\u00e9\n}}\n'''South Island School''' ({{zh|t=\u5357\u5cf6\u4e2d\u5b78}}) is a private school founded by the [[English Schools Foundation]] of Hong Kong, and is located at 50 Nam Fung Road, [[Aberdeen, Hong Kong|Aberdeen]], [[Hong Kong]], with about 1,400 students enrolled and 107 teachers. Students come from diverse backgrounds, with over 38 nationalities represented. The school offers the [[GCSE]]/[[IGCSE]] syllabus, [[IB Diploma Programme]], IB Career-related Programme and the [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTEC]] qualification. The school is one of three ESF secondary schools on Hong Kong Island, the others being [[West Island School]] and [[Island School]].\n\nAccording to an inspection report from 2019 by the Council of International Schools (CoIS) and the Western Association of Schools and Colleges (WASC), South Island School 'passionately promotes the development of global citizenship and intercultural learning, and the school climate is such that there is a very strong sense of mutual trust amongst all the school\u2019s stakeholders.'<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School \u2013 A Celebration of Excellence |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/south-island-school-a-celebration-of-excellence/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nIn 1977, South Island School was founded as an annex of [[Island School]], a fellow [[English Schools Foundation]] School. The school opened with 165 students and 6 teachers, with three classes in Form 1, and one class in Form 2 and Form 3 respectively. Mike Taylor was the first principal. \n\nThe school moved to its current location at 50 Nam Fung Road in 1983. It consisted of the [[Ching Ling Soong]] Block and an outdoor swimming pool.<ref>{{cite web |title=The History of South Island School |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/history/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the school grew in size, more facilities were required. The next big change to the school came with the construction of the Stephen Hawking Building (named after physicist [[Stephen Hawking]]), and the swimming pool became an indoor one with the Sports Block being built on top of it, allowing for year-round swimming lessons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sis.edu.hk/Warps/Principal%20Msg/Autumn%2004.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-10-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051113033219/http://www.sis.edu.hk/Warps/Principal%20Msg/Autumn%2004.html |archivedate=13 November 2005 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBy 2003, the increase in student population warranted the construction of a new school block. Construction began on a new eight-storey building that would accompany the C Block and the S Block. By 2004, the new block was completed and was named the Da Vinci (after Italian polymath, [[Leonardo da Vinci]]) Block.\n\nIn the school year of 2007-2008, the school was accredited to teach the IB Diploma programme. The IB Centre was opened, a section of the school designated for [[International Baccalaureate]] students in Years 12 and 13. This was renamed the Diploma Centre in the school year of 2009-2010. \n\nIn November 2010, the new John Wray Atrium, named after previous principal, John Wray, opened for all students.\n\nIn the following years, many of the school facilities underwent renovations. The library in the C Block was renovated in the summer holidays of 2012 and re-opened in late September the same year, and was renamed as the \"Learning Resource Center\". In November of 2012, the renovation of the library was completed, and was reopened as the Learning Resources Centre (LRC).\n\nIn February of 2014, additional floors were added to the Sports Block to create The Space, a multipurpose learning space. There is also an astroturf on top of the Space which was completed in the same year. In November, the school completed a redesigned School Hall with state-of-the-art facilities and a 400-seat auditorium.\n\nIn 2016, South Island School adopted the Middle Years Program and the IB CP (career-related) programme. The IB CP was offered in addition to the IB Diploma programme, which places greater emphasis on developing vocational skills. The programme combines academic courses from the IB Diploma programme with the career-related experiences of the BTEC courses to create a personalised and career-focused pathway for students.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School's new IB curriculum offer |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/south-island-schools-new-ib-curriculum-offer/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=23 September 2016}}</ref> Also in the same year, the School Foyer and the Refectory were renovated.\n\nIn 2017, South Island School celebrated its 40th anniversary. Students and staff walked down to Deep Water Bay Beach for charity and participated in activities commemorating the event, such as a time capsule and an art mural.<ref>{{cite web |title=Student Council: Catering, Interhouse and more on SIS40 |url=https://www.facebook.com/notes/south-island-school-student-council/6617-catering-interhouse-and-more-on-sis-40/1371531516268749/ |website=SIS Student Council Facebook page |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> A giant birthday cake was also made, with enough cake for every teacher and student in the school. Later that October, an exhibition was shown in the Atrium commemorating the school's history \n<ref>{{cite web |title=SIS 40th Birthday Celebration - Archive Exhibition Tour |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/sis-40th-birthday-celebration-archive-exhibition-tour/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=27 October 2017}}</ref>, and an alumni gathering was held in Hong Kong.\n\nIn 2018, the Food Technology laboratories were renovated, along with the Science classrooms on the 6th floor. In 2019, the classrooms on the 3rd and 4th floors of the C Block were also renovated.\n\n== Governance ==\n\nSouth Island School is part of the English Schools Foundation of 22 schools<ref name=\"About ESF\">{{cite web |title=About ESF |url=https://www.esf.edu.hk/about-esf/ |website=ESF |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> in Hong Kong that operates within the ESF government ordinance.\n\nThe school is accountable to the Board of Governors (Executive Committee) of [[English Schools Foundation]] and its local governing body: School Council. The council meets around six times per year. It has two sub-committees, namely Finance & Personnel (FP) and Learning and Professional Development (LPD) both chaired by community representatives. Among other matters, the FP sub-committee reviews the school's annual budget and recommends acceptance to the full council. It also reviews personnel matters and considers health & safety issues. The LPD subcommittee's work is more aimed at, inter alia, curriculum development, teaching methods and examination performance.<ref>http://www.sis.edu.hk/about-us/school-council</ref>\n\n== Academics ==\n\n=== Curriculum ===\nBetween Year 7 and Year 9, students take the Middle Years Programme (MYP) offered by the International Baccalaureate. The MYP is usually a 5-year programme, but the programme was shortened to 3 years so that the IGCSE programme could still be offered. During Year 7 and 8, all students follow a common curriculum, which includes English, Maths, Science, Chinese, a modern foreign language (French or Spanish), Individuals and Societies, Global Thinking, design, and the arts. At the end of Year 9, all students participate in the Community Project. Students work in groups to investigate, propose, plan and implement a project that serves a need within the school community or the wider Hong Kong community.<ref>{{cite web |title=Family Bauhinia Newsletter (June 2019) |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/family-bauhinia-newsletter-june-2019/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |location=Curriculum Update |date=27 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring Year 10 and 11, students follow the I/GCSE curriculum. All students must take English, Mathematics, Sciences (Biology, Chemistry, Physics), PE (examined or non-examined), a language, a humanities subject, and Global Citizenship. In addition, students can choose to take either another language, or another humanities subject.<ref>{{cite web |title=Y10-11 Curriculum |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/academic/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn Year 12 and 13, students can either choose to do the IB Diploma or the IB Career-related Programme. For the Diploma Programme, students must choose 3 Higher Level subjects and 3 Standard Level subjects, where subjects in the student's first language, additional Language, the humanities, the sciences, mathematics are required. Students also need to complete the Extended Essay, CAS, and the Theory of Knowledge course. Students in the Career-related Programme can choose to substitute some of their IB DP subjects with more applied BTEC subjects, but must still complete the CP core.\n\n=== Higher Education Destinations ===\n\nIn 2019, 40% of South Island School students matriculate to the [[United Kingdom]], 19% to [[Hong Kong]], 13% to the [[United States]], 9% to [[Canada]], 6% to either [[Australia]] or New Zealand, and the remainder matriculate to countries such as [[Korea]] and [[Japan]]. In Hong Kong, 17 students chose to study at the [[University of Hong Kong]], five to [[HKUST]] and six to the [[Chinese University of Hong Kong]], while in the UK, 6 students matriculated to [[Imperial College]] and [[University College London|UCL]]. In addition, the most popular universities in Canada were the [[University of British Columbia]] and the [[University of Toronto]] with five students each. \n\nSouth Island School graduates usually apply to a range of courses. Fields such as Economics, and Business and Management have been consistently popular among South Island School graduates. Ten students each have matriculated to the traditionally popular Law and Psychology courses. The social sciences remain popular: a particular favourite is Psychology, with 11 students choosing this as their major. 20 students pursued creative degrees such as Design, Film and Performing Arts as well.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School Higher Education Destinations 2019 |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/careers-and-higher-education/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Examination Results ===\nIn 2012, 3 students scored the maximum 45 points on the IB Diploma (out of 109 worldwide), and another 5 students scored 44 points. 32% of the graduating body scored 40 points or more. The mean score was 36.3 out of 45, in comparison to the world average of 30.1.<ref>{{cite web|title=IB Results - July 2012|url=http://www.sis.edu.hk/learning-sis/exams-information/ib-exam-results|accessdate=22 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130114014713/http://www.sis.edu.hk/learning-sis/exams-information/ib-exam-results|archive-date=14 January 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, 2 students scored the maximum 45 points on the IB Diploma, while three others scored 44, and a further six scored 43, exceeding international averages by substantial margins. In 2018, 98% of students achieved the full IB Diploma, compared to 78.4% worldwide. That year, the mean score for all IB Diploma students was 35.0 in comparison to the world average of 30.0. Furthermore, 22% of students at South Island School achieved 30 or more points, compared to 8% worldwide.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School: IB Diploma Provisional Results (May 2018) |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/IB-Results-2018_for-website.pdf |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Students ==\n\nStudents come from diverse backgrounds, with 38 nationalities represented as of 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=For New Families |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/for-new-families/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |location=Student's Welcome}}</ref> In 2019, the most represented was those with United Kingdom citizenship. As of that year, 50% of the students were ethnic Chinese, 14% were Caucasian, 8% were Eurasian, 7% were Indian, and 21% were of other races<ref>{{cite web |title=Annual Report 2018-2019 |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/annual-report-2018-2019/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |page=27 |date=1 November 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe school is non-selective towards academic ability and reserves 24 places in the Learning Support Unit for students with additional learning needs.\n\n== Student Leadership ==\n\n=== Prefect Team ===\nThe school has a well-established prefect system in which the Year 12 and Year 13 students are assigned key positions of responsibility to help with the day-to-day operations of the school. Serving as chief representatives of the student body is the Head Prefect team, led by the Head Boy and Head Girl. The Head Prefect Team is selected through a rigorous process that includes written applications, student and teacher voting, a panel interview, and a final interview with the Principal, Vice Principal, and a School Council member.\n\n=== Student Council ===\n\n=== Sustainability Council ===\nThe Sustainability Council, or SusCo in short are a student group that promote environmental awareness in South Island School. Aside from installing water fountains and recycling bins around the school, they have installed solar panels on the roof of the D Block.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Environmental Sustainability Group |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/the-environmental-sustainability-group/ |accessdate=1 December 2019}}</ref> They have also sold reusable cutlery sets in January of 2019 in response to the loss of metal cutlery from the school cafeteria. In March, they raised awareness of environmental issues by organising a 'Green Week'. During this week, they organised a talk raising awareness about plastic use, served meatless meals in the cafeteria for one day, and conducted a 'Power Down Day' where no electrical devices were allowed to be used. In August, they successfully introduced reusable bowls, plates and containers to replace the disposable plates and cups for snacks.<ref>{{cite web |title=Green Catering at SIS |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/next-week-is-green-week/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=19 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Making a Difference Council ===\nThe MaD Council are a student group that promotes the school's philosophy of 'Making A Difference'. They are responsible for organising and making decisions for MaD Week, a week where students go overseas or stay in Hong Kong to make a difference to themselves and the community around them. In addition, they work with the House Councils to organise school events and initiatives, such as each House's MaD Weeks, as well as the student-led events.\n\n=== Digital Leaders ===\nThe Digital Leaders are a student group involved in organising technology-related initiatives at South Island School. They have worked with Year 8 InterD students and have supported them in the media literacy unit, as well as supported the Laptop Induction evenings for Year 7s. They have also organised a photography club and coding club, as well as organised an 'Internet Safety Week'.<ref>{{cite web |title=Digital Leadership Team |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/digital-leadership-team/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=26 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Internet Safety Week 2019 |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/internet-safety-week-2019-monday-11th-february-monday-18th-february/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Houses ==\nStudents at South Island School were originally allocated into one of seven houses, named after notable people in history. These houses were:\n\n* Hillary (blue)\n* Tolstoy (red)\n* Aylward (yellow)\n* Schweitzer (green)\n* Jefferson (purple)\n* Marden (orange)\n* Nobel (light blue)\n\nThese 7 houses later were then reorganised to form six houses and were named after the word 'House' in six different languages. \n\nThese houses, along with their respective colours and the language where their name originates from, are:\n\n* Bahay (Yellow) - [[Filipino language|Filipino]]\n* Casa (Red) - [[Spanish language|Spanish]]\n* Shtepi (Green) - [[Albanian language|Albanian]]\n* Maison (Blue) - [[French language|French]]\n* Ku\u0107a (Purple) - [[Croatian language|Croatian]]\n* Namas (Orange) - [[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]\n\nThe house colours were allocated after each head of house pulled slips of paper from a hat with a colour written on them. In each year, a house consists of two tutor groups of about 18 students, headed by a tutor of one tutor group, who oversee the students' well-being and performance in school. There is a small 10-minute period at the beginning of each weekday (except for Tuesdays, where the tutor period lasts for half an hour, and Fridays, where there is also another half an hour period before school ends) where all students meet with their tutors. The houses are then grouped into three separate \"Learning Families\", named [[Bamboo]] (consisting of students in Years 9-13 in the Kuca, Maison and Namas houses), [[Banyan]] (consisting of students in Years 9-13 in the Bahay, Casa and Shtepi houses), and [[Bauhinia]] (all students in Years 7-8). Each house is headed by a Head of House which liaises with student leaders in that particular house.\n\n== Sports and Activities ==\nExtra-curricular activities at the school include [[debating]], [[Model United Nations|MUN]], [[squash (sport)|squash]], [[netball]], [[basketball]], [[Association football|football]], [[swimming (sport)|swimming]], [[chess]], [[tennis]], singing, [[Rugby football|rugby]], [[field hockey]], [[cricket]] and more. Every student is obliged to take part in inter-house [[sport of athletics|athletics]], and inter-house swimming. As well as inter-house competitions, South Island School competes in various inter-school competitions such as basketball and football. There are also musical activities culminating in a range of performances throughout the year.<ref>[http://www.sis.edu.hk/index.aspx?nodeid=1162&langNo=1 South Island School - Activities Programme<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926232701/http://www.sis.edu.hk/index.aspx?nodeid=1162&langNo=1 |date=26 September 2007 }}</ref> \n\nIn 2019, South Island School beat Island School to win the All Hong Kong Schools Jing Ying Football Tournament. This was the first time that the school has won.<ref>{{cite web |title=South Island School won the 2019 Jing Ying Football Tournament |url=https://www.sis.edu.hk/south-island-school-won-the-2019-jing-ying-football-tournament/ |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=22 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author1=Joanne Ma |title=South Island School defeats Island School in Jing Ying Football Tournament |url=All Hong Kong Schools Jing Ying Football Tournament |website=Young Post |accessdate=1 December 2019 |date=March 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe school also organises events such as Nightfest, International Evening, the Innovation Fashion Show, [[Diwali]] Night, the ICM yearly fundraiser, etc. Such events are wholly managed by the student body.\n\n== Campus and Facilities ==\n\nThe school's campus is in the south side of [[Hong Kong Island]] against the backdrop of [[Mount Nicholson]], facing the [[South China Sea]]. It is in a semi-rural location. Students have their own locker and form room. For Years 12 to 13, there is a dedicated study facility and common room space.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sis.edu.hk/about-us/campus-and-facilities |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-08-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428231946/http://www.sis.edu.hk/about-us/campus-and-facilities |archivedate=28 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nFacilities include:\n* The Space (multi-purpose venue)\n* The John Wray Atrium (contains a cafeteria) \n* 25m Indoor Swimming Pool\n* Sports Hall\n* Fitness Gym\n* Artificial Astro Turf\n* 2 Outdoor Playgrounds (Upper and Lower) \n* Covered Playground\n* Covered Multi-Sports Area\n* Hall\n* 2 Drama Studios\n* 12 Science Laboratories\n* 4 Design Technology Workshops\n* 2 Food Technology Workshops\n* 2 Large Art Rooms\n* 3 Media Studies Rooms\n* 2 Music Rooms (Contains 6 smaller music rooms)\n* Refectory\n* Cafe\n* Learning Resource Centre (Library)\n* Diploma Centre\n\n==See also==\n* [[English Schools Foundation]]\n* [[List of English Schools Foundation schools]]\n* [[List of international schools in Hong Kong]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|South Island School}}\n*[http://www.sis.edu.hk/ Official website]\n{{Southern District, Hong Kong}}\n{{International schools in Hong Kong}}\n{{Esfschool}}\n{{coord|22.2539|114.1831|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1977]]\n[[Category:English Schools Foundation schools]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:Aberdeen, Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:International Baccalaureate schools in Hong Kong]]\n[[Category:1977 establishments in Hong Kong]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 9-13 \u2192 9\u201313 (2), November of 2012 \u2192 November 2012 (3), \u2019s \u2192 's, 2007-2008 \u2192 2007\u20132008 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Island_School"}
{"title_page": "Cabinet Erdo\u011fan IV", "text_new": "{{Infobox government cabinet\n| cabinet_name            = Fourth Erdo\u011fan Cabinet<br>{{small|''D\u00f6rd\u00fcnc\u00fc Erdo\u011fan H\u00fck\u00fcmeti''}}\n| jurisdiction            = Turkey\n| cabinet_number          = 66th\n| flag                    = Flag_of_Turkey.svg\n| incumbent               = 9 July 2018\n| image                   = Recep Tayyip Erdogan 2017.jpg\n| date_formed             = 10 July 2018\n| date_dissolved          = \n| government_head         = [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]\n| deputy government_head  = \n| government_head_history =\n| state_head              = [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan]]\n| current_number          = \n| former_members_number   =\n| total_number            = \n| political_party         = [[Justice and Development Party (Turkey)|Justice and Development Party]]<br>[[Independent politician|Independent(s)]]\n| legislature_status      = {{Longitem|[[Minority government|Minority]]<br /><small>''with [[People's Alliance (Turkey)|MHP and BBP confidence & supply]]''</small>}}\n| opposition_cabinet      =\n| opposition_party        = [[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|Republican People's Party]] <br/> [[\u0130yi Parti|Good Party]]\n| opposition_leader       = [[Kemal K\u0131l\u0131\u00e7daro\u011flu]]\n| election                = \n| legislature_term        =\n| outgoing_formation      =\n| previous                = [[Y\u0131ld\u0131r\u0131m Cabinet]]\n| successor               = \n}}\n\nThe '''Fourth Erdo\u011fan Cabinet''' is the 66th government of the [[Turkey|Republic of Turkey]], which was declared on 9 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=President Erdo\u011fan announces ministers of Turkey's new cabinet |url=http://www.hurriyetdailynews.com/president-erdogan-announces-ministers-of-turkeys-new-cabinet-134375 |website=H\u00fcrriyet Daily News |accessdate=10 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref> It is the first cabinet after Turkey's transition into [[presidential republic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Erdogan announces first cabinet under new presidential system |url=https://www.trtworld.com/turkey/erdogan-announces-first-cabinet-under-new-presidential-system-18792 |website=[[TRT World]] |accessdate=10 July 2018 |language=tr-TR}}</ref> It was also the first cabinet that did not require [[Grand National Assembly of Turkey|parliamentary]] approval to be formed.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Editorial |first1=Reuters |title=Turkey's Erdogan to name cabinet as signals action on economy |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-politics-erdogan/turkeys-erdogan-to-name-cabinet-as-signals-action-on-economy-idUSKBN1JX0D1 |website=U.S. |accessdate=10 July 2018 |quote=...Erdogan will select his own cabinet and regulate ministries and remove civil servants, all without parliamentary approval. ...}}</ref>\n\n==Changes==\nIn this new system, the number of ministries were reduced to 16 from 26. A statutory decree was issued to merge several ministries, and also to abolish certain organizational and functional laws of some ministries and institutions.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey: Decree out making first changes in new system |url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/todays-headlines/turkey-decree-out-making-first-changes-in-new-system/1199042 |website=Anadolu Agency |accessdate=15 July 2018 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Previous name\n! Current name\n|-\n| Ministry of Labour and Social Security\n| rowspan=2 valign=center|Ministry of Labour, Social Services and Family\n|-\n| Ministry of Family and Social Policy\n|-\n| Ministry of Science, Industry and Technology\n| rowspan=2 valign=center|Ministry of Industry and Technology\n|-\n| Ministry of Development\n|-\n| Ministry of Customs and Trade\n| rowspan=2 valign=center|Ministry of Trade\n|-\n| Ministry of Economic Affairs\n|-\n| Ministry of Food, Agriculture and Livestock\n| rowspan=2 valign=center|Ministry of Agriculture and Forest\n|-\n| Ministry of Forest and Water Management\n|-\n| Ministry of Finan